.\" SKINT.1.in  --  man page template for SKINT
.\" substitute @VERSION@, @DATE@, @LIBDIR@ at build time
.TH SKINT 1 "@DATE@" "SKINT @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
skint \- cheap and fast R7RS Scheme interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B skint
[\fIOPTION\fR]... [\fIFILE\fR] [\fIARG\fR]...
.br
.PP
If no \fIFILE\fR is given, an interactive Read-Eval-Print loop is started.
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBskint\fR is a small, self-contained interpreter for the R7RS-small
Scheme language.  All standard libraries are built-in; more than 100
SRFIs can be loaded from the optional external library tree.
.PP
When \fIFILE\fR is supplied it is executed as a Scheme script
(SRFI-22 semantics) after which \fBskint\fR exits.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Increase output verbosity.
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Suppress non-essential messages.
.TP
.BR \-A ", " \-\-append\-libdir =\fIDIR\fR
Append \fIDIR\fR to the library search path.
.TP
.BR \-I ", " \-\-prepend\-libdir =\fIDIR\fR
Prepend \fIDIR\fR to the library search path.
.TP
.BR \-D ", " \-\-define\-feature =\fINAME\fR
Add \fINAME\fR to the (features) list.
.TP
.BR \-U ", " \-\-undef\-feature =\fINAME\fR
Remove \fINAME\fR from the (features) list.
.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-eval =\fISEXP\fR
Evaluate and print \fISEXP\fR, then continue.
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-load =\fIFILE\fR
Load \fIFILE\fR and continue.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-script =\fIFILE\fR
Run \fIFILE\fR as a script (SRFI-22).
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-program =\fIFILE\fR
Run \fIFILE\fR as a program (non-script mode).
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Show version (in SRFI 176 format) and exit.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show help and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-
Ends option processing; remaining arguments are passed to the script.

.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B SKINT_LIBDIRS
Colon-separated list of directories searched for `.sld` libraries.  If unset the default is
.IR ./ : lib/ : @LIBDIR@/

.SH FILES
.TP
.I @LIBDIR@/
External library tree (`.sld` modules) installed by \fBmake libinstall\fR.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Interactive REPL:
.B skint
.TP
Interactive REPL with command line editing:
.B rlwrap skint
.TP
Run a script:
.B skint -s hello.scm arg1 arg2
.TP
Evaluate an expression:
.B skint -e '(display (+ 1 2 3)) (newline)'
.TP
Load a file then enter REPL:
.B skint -l init.scm

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
successful execution
.TP
.B 1
syntax or runtime error
.TP
.B 2
command-line usage error

